"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904811","Department for Transport","false","2018-05-23","<p>The Department announced in February 2018 that it would develop bidding guidance later this year for authorities that want to set up lane rental schemes. It also announced that approval will be subject to certain conditions. These include that authorities must have a well-run permit scheme in place; schemes would apply to an authorities’ own works; charges should be used to encourage certain behaviour e.g. more joint works; and schemes should be trialled for a period of time. Finally, it would like to see authorities put in place caps for some major works so that these are not unfairly penalised.</p><p> </p><p>The relevant legislation allows local authorities to charge up to £2,500 per day on the busiest roads at the busiest times. Authorities can offer discounts and waive charges in certain circumstances.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","144411 ; 144412 ; 144414","2018-05-23T08:33:51.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904811/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904811/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904811/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-15","Road Works: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether there is a cap on lane rental scheme charges for major works to (a) install and (b) replace apparatus.","false","Biography information for Luke Pollard","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Luke Pollard","144413"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904812","Department for Transport","false","2018-05-23","<p>The Department announced in February 2018 that it would develop bidding guidance later this year for authorities that want to set up lane rental schemes. It also announced that approval will be subject to certain conditions. These include that authorities must have a well-run permit scheme in place; schemes would apply to an authorities’ own works; charges should be used to encourage certain behaviour e.g. more joint works; and schemes should be trialled for a period of time. Finally, it would like to see authorities put in place caps for some major works so that these are not unfairly penalised.</p><p> </p><p>The relevant legislation allows local authorities to charge up to £2,500 per day on the busiest roads at the busiest times. Authorities can offer discounts and waive charges in certain circumstances.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","144411 ; 144412 ; 144413","2018-05-23T08:33:51.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904812/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904812/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904812/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-15","Road Works: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what (a) discounts and (c) fee waivers from lane rental schemes are available for joint works; and what definition his Department uses for joint works.","false","Biography information for Luke Pollard","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Luke Pollard","144414"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904813","Department for Transport","false","2018-05-23","<p>Lane rental applies to works on the local road network and can be set up and operated by local highway authorities. Charges apply to street works carried out by utility companies and can be applied to highway road works carried out by local authorities. It will not apply for Highways England.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-05-23T09:07:51.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904813/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904813/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904813/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-15","Road Works: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether lane rental scheme charges will apply to street works undertaken by the Highways Agency.","false","Biography information for Luke Pollard","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Luke Pollard","144415"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904814","Department for Transport","false","2018-05-23","<p>At the end of each Franchisee Year the Department, in accordance with the Franchise Agreement, will calculate the Performance Sum payable by the Secretary of State to the Franchisee or required to be incurred by the Franchisee, these are known as Performance Sum Payments.</p><p> </p><p>Where following calculation of the Cancellations Performance Sum, the TOC Minute Delay Performance Sum and/or the Short Formation Performance Sum, the Franchisee is required to incur expenditure, the Franchisee shall incur expenditure equal to the amount for each to secure improvement to the Franchisee's performance in that area to meet its targets, this is known as Required Performance Improvement.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","144181","2018-05-23T08:58:50.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904814/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904814/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904814/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-15","Northern: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much Northern has been fined for cancellations and partial cancellations since Arriva took over that franchise.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Sir David Crausby","144180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904815","Department for Transport","false","2018-05-23","<p>At the end of each Franchisee Year the Department, in accordance with the Franchise Agreement, will calculate the Performance Sum payable by the Secretary of State to the Franchisee or required to be incurred by the Franchisee, these are known as Performance Sum Payments.</p><p> </p><p>Where following calculation of the Cancellations Performance Sum, the TOC Minute Delay Performance Sum and/or the Short Formation Performance Sum, the Franchisee is required to incur expenditure, the Franchisee shall incur expenditure equal to the amount for each to secure improvement to the Franchisee's performance in that area to meet its targets, this is known as Required Performance Improvement.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","144180","2018-05-23T08:58:50.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904815/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904815/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904815/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-15","Northern: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much Network Rail has paid out to Northern in compensation for cancellations since Arriva took over that franchise.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Sir David Crausby","144181"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904816","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-05-21","<p>My rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy and his officials have been working closely with businesses across a range sectors, as well as other government departments, to understand the impacts of future customs arrangements, including any rules of origin, on businesses and the economy . As my rt. hon. Friend the Prime Minister has stated, we are committed to ensuring that trade between the UK and the EU is as frictionless as possible.</p><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2018-05-21T07:59:13.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904816/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904816/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904816/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-05-15","Rules of Origin","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of rules of origin under the proposed maximum facilitation model on the manufacturing sector.","false","Biography information for Antoinette Sandbach","Eddisbury","Antoinette Sandbach","144365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904817","Department for Transport","false","2018-05-23","<p>The Department for Transport has not met with trade union representatives in respect with the ongoing Northern industrial dispute. This dispute is between the unions and the train operator, however the Government has been doing all it can to ensure passenger disruption is minimised. Ministers have met with the leadership of ASLEF and RMT to discuss wider ranging issues.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-05-23T09:02:48.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904817/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904817/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904817/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-15","Northern: Industrial Disputes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what meetings he has had with trades union representatives in respect of the ongoing Northern industrial dispute.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Sir David Crausby","144182"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904818","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-05-21","<p>​The Government takes its defence exports responsibilities extremely seriously. We operate some of the most robust export controls in the world. We have no information to suggest that UK supplied equipment has been used in contravention of UK arms licensing criteria.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-05-21T16:47:32.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904818/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904818/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904818/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-15","Israel: Arms Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to investigate allegations of Israel’s contravention of UK national arms licensing criteria.","false","Biography information for Ann Clwyd","Cynon Valley","Ann Clwyd","144212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904819","Treasury","false","2018-05-21","<p>As the Home Secretary has set out, the Government is committed to putting right the wrongs experienced by the Windrush generation, and is clear that where people have suffered loss they will be compensated. The Home Office is still working through the detail of what this scheme will look like, including potential costs to the department.</p><p> </p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2018-05-21T12:17:19.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904819/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904819/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904819/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-15","Immigration: Windrush Generation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate has been of made the cost to the public purse of the (a) total and (b) additional staffing costs of the Windrush compensation programme.","false","Biography information for Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","Tooting","Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","144377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904820","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-05-21","<p>Other than for those who are terminally ill, Personal Independence Payment (PIP) is assessed on the basis of the needs arising from a long-term health condition or disability rather than a diagnosis. The three month qualifying period is one of the tests that determines whether an individual meets that definition. Claims can be submitted during the qualifying period</p><p> </p><p>PIP claimants who are terminally ill do not have to satisfy the three month qualifying period, have their claim fast tracked and are eligible for the enhanced rate daily living component from the date of claim.</p><p> </p><p>Financial and practical support may be available during the qualifying period, for example Employment and Support Allowance, the Healthcare Travel Costs Scheme or support provided by a Local Authority.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-05-21T10:32:34.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904820/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904820/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904820/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-15","Personal Independence Payment: Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if her Department will make an assessment of the financial effect of the three-month waiting period for personal independence payment on people who have received a cancer diagnosis.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","144155"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904821","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-05-21","<p>The Foreign Secretary discussed the use of live ammunition against protestors in Gaza with Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu on 16 May. I also raised concerns regarding this issue with my Israeli counterpart on 13 May and with the Israeli ambassador to the UK on 17 May. As I said in my statement of 14 May, we continue to implore Israel to show greater restraint in its use of live fire.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-05-21T16:50:00.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904821/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904821/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904821/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-15","Israel: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his Israeli counterpart on the use of live ammunition against Palestinian protesters.","false","Biography information for Ann Clwyd","Cynon Valley","Ann Clwyd","144213"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904822","Department for Education","false","2018-05-23","<p>Following the meeting I had with my hon. Friend the Member for Morecambe and Lunesdale and his constituents about early intervention and resourcing, my officials subsequently spoke to Lancashire County Council’s Director of Children’s Services to relay the matters discussed. I understand the Director of Children’s Services has followed up with my hon. Friend the Member for Morecambe and Lunesdale’s constituent.</p><p> </p><p>Funding for children’s services is an un-ring-fenced part of the wider local government finance settlement, to give local authorities the flexibility to focus on locally determined priorities and, of course, their statutory responsibilities, including children’s social care. Over the five year period from 2015-16 to 2019-20 councils will have access to more than £200 billion to deliver the local services their communities want to see, including children’s services. In February, Parliament confirmed the 2018-19 settlement for local government, providing a real terms increase in resources available to local government - £44.3 billion in 2017-18 to £45.1 billion in 2018-19.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-05-23T13:19:32.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904822/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904822/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904822/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-15","Children: Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent discussions his Department has had with the Lancashire Director of Children's Services on early intervention, resourcing and identified or non-funding pressures.","false","Biography information for David Morris","Morecambe and Lunesdale","David Morris","144277"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904823","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-05-21","<p>Since 2011, the Ministry of Defence has spent, on average, £20 million per year with Ascent to provide flying training. This does not include additional costs, for example those associated with fuel, the operation of stations, or military personnel costs, which could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2018-05-21T15:48:48.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904823/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904823/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904823/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-05-15","Military Aircraft: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the annual in-year costs for operating the UK Military Flying Training System have been in each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","144221"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904824","Department for Transport","false","2018-05-23","<p><strong> </strong>The Department does not hold this level of information. Cancellation information provided to the Department by the Train operators are at a total percentage per period basis.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-05-23T09:05:28.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904824/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904824/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904824/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-15","Northern: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many Northern services have been cancelled due to staffing issues in each month since Arriva took over that franchise.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Sir David Crausby","144183"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904825","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-05-22","<p>Working with Trussell Trust we undertook a 12 week telephony hotline trial during the summer 2017, in three Districts (Durham and Tees Valley, Northumberland and Cambridgeshire), to assess the volume and nature of enquiries made by claimants from their linked food banks.</p><p> </p><p>The small number of calls made to the hotline seemed to indicate that demand for Jobcentre resource in food banks was low. However, it was agreed that we would remind colleagues of the signposting process, and District Partnership teams would continue to engage with food banks as part of their portfolio of local partners and stakeholders.</p><p> </p><p>Jobcentres continue to engage with food banks or organisations hosting food banks as part of their normal partnership work. To ensure a consistent offer, an assurance was received in February 2018 that each Jobcentre Single Point of Contact had made contact with their linked food banks to increase and maintain partnership working.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-05-22T14:19:37.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904825/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904825/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904825/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-15","Food Banks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what progress her Department has made on rolling out a  programme of placing an officer of her Department into local food banks to assist with benefits (a) access and (b) problems as first piloted in Morecambe.","false","Biography information for David Morris","Morecambe and Lunesdale","David Morris","144278"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904826","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-22","<p>The papers from the project are currently being finalised by the Small Area Health Statistics Unit and will be submitted to peer reviewed journals by the end of June 2018. It is likely to be a few months after submission for the papers to be published.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-05-22T15:38:33.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904826/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904826/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904826/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-15","Incinerators","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, on what date the study on incinerators by the Small Area Health Statistics Unit is planned to be published.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","144246"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904827","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-05-21","<p>The number of RAF Sentinel R1 aircraft in the Forward and Sustainment Fleets at the beginning of each month for 2017 is given in the table below:</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong>Sentinel</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Month</strong> <strong>2017</strong></p></td><td><p>Forward Fleet</p></td><td><p>Sustainment Fleet</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>January</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>February</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>March</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>May</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>June</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>July</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>August</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>September</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>October</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>November</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>December</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Forward Fleet comprises serviceable and short term unserviceable aircraft. Typically, the short term unserviceable aircraft are undergoing minor works, forward maintenance or any other unforeseen rectification or technical inspection that can arise on a day-to-day basis. The sustainment fleet includes aircraft undergoing deep maintenance, upgrade programmes or being held in storage. The number of aircraft available varies day-to-day, according to normal fleet management activities. The above figures include Sentinel ZJ693 which was placed in long term storage on 1 April 2017</p><p> </p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2018-05-21T15:30:23.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904827/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904827/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904827/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-05-15","Sentinel Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many RAF Sentinel R1 aircraft were serviceable on the first day of each month of 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","144222"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904828","Cabinet Office","false","2018-05-21","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2018-05-21T10:45:55.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904828/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904828/answer","PQ144247 final.pdf","UKSA Response ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904828/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-05-15","Exports: EU Countries and USA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment he has made of trends in the level of exports to (a) the USA and (b) the EU since 2011.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","144247"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904829","Treasury","false","2018-05-23","<p>The government-commissioned Money Advice Service (MAS) funds centrally-coordinated, publicly-funded debt advice. MAS spent just under £49m to provide over 440,000 debt advice sessions in 2016-17. This year, MAS’ budget will rise to over £56m – enough to provide support to 530,000 people.</p><p> </p><p>To support this work, the government is also setting up a new single financial guidance body, which will bring together public-funded money and pensions guidance, and debt advice services. The new body will enable the public to get support with all aspects of their financial lives quickly and easily.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-05-23T15:37:25.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904829/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904829/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904829/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-15","Debts: Advisory Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent steps his Department has taken to (a) publicise and (b) support debt advice services.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Sir David Crausby","144184"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904830","Treasury","false","2018-05-23","<p>The government remains committed to supporting credit unions, which provide vital services to financially under-served communities and contribute to the diversity of the UK’s financial services sector. To improve access to credit unions, government has:</p><p>· In April 2018, announced increased funding for a scheme which incentivises credit union membership in areas at risk of being targeted by loan sharks. This will help vulnerable people to borrow and save with a safe and responsible financial provider, and promote credit unions as an alternative source of credit.</p><p>· At Autumn Budget 2017, announced that the credit union ‘common bond’ limit, which applies to credit unions whose membership is based around a local area, would be raised from 2 to 3 million. This change came into force in April this year, and will allow the larger credit unions to expand and help the sector to consolidate.</p><p>· In 2014, raised the statutory cap on the total interest a credit union can charge on loans from 2 to 3% per month. This has allowed credit unions to expand into new markets, and compete more effectively with other lenders.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-05-23T15:36:15.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904830/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904830/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904830/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-15","Credit Unions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent steps his Department has taken to improve and promote access to credit unions.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Sir David Crausby","144185"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904831","Treasury","false","2018-05-23","<p>The latest tax credit overpayment statistics available relate to the financial year 2015-16 and statistics relating to the financial year 2016-17 are due to be released this summer.</p><p> </p><p>Based on the available statistics relating to 2015-16, there were 1.4m overpaid tax credit awards, which amounted to £1.572m in overpayments. This figure can be found on page 8 of the Child and Working Tax Credits, Finalised Annual Awards, Supplement on Payments National Statistics, and is available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/617181/Child_and_Working_Tax_Credits_statistics_finalised_annual_awards__supplement_on_payments_-_2015_to_2016.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/617181/Child_and_Working_Tax_Credits_statistics_finalised_annual_awards__supplement_on_payments_-_2015_to_2016.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>Information regarding the estimated cost of recovering such overpayments can only be made available at disproportionate cost.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2018-05-23T09:22:54.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904831/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904831/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904831/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-15","Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much his Department overpaid in tax credit claims in the last financial year; and what the estimated cost is of recovering those overpayments.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Sir David Crausby","144186"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904832","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-05-23","<p>Over the course of this spending period the Government has made available over £200 billion of funding for local government, for councils to spend on locally determined priorities, including sports facilities.</p><p>Sport England works with a wide range of local authorities, providing expert advice and funding to sustain and increase the number of people playing sport regularly.</p><p>It invests in local authority facilities projects through its range of funding programmes to make sure that facilities are modern, accessible and in the right places to have the most impact.</p><p>Full details of the local government finance settlement are here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/final-local-government-finance-settlement-england-2018-to-2019" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/final-local-government-finance-settlement-england-2018-to-2019</a></p><p />","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak",,"2018-05-23T15:55:11.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904832/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904832/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904832/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-05-15","Local Government Finance: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what information his Department holds on the amount of money spent by local authorities in the North West on sports and leisure in each of the last five financial years.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Sir David Crausby","144187"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904833","Department for Education","false","2018-05-23","<p>The information requested is not held centrally. Safeguarding concerns are a matter for local determination and would not be routinely reported to government.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-05-23T12:41:02.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904833/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904833/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904833/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-15","Children: Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what reports of concern have been submitted to the Lancashire Children's Safeguarding Board on (a) Morecambe Bay Primary School and (b) West End Primary School in the last three years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for David Morris","Morecambe and Lunesdale","David Morris","144279"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904834","Treasury","false","2018-05-23","<p>The latest published estimates on take-up of tax credits are available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/child-benefit-child-tax-credit-ctc-and-working-tax-credit-wtc-take-up-rates-2015-to-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/child-benefit-child-tax-credit-ctc-and-working-tax-credit-wtc-take-up-rates-2015-to-2016</a></p><p>The publication includes estimates of unclaimed tax credit entitlements for 2015-16. 2016-17 estimates are expected to be released in December 2018.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2018-05-23T09:21:21.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904834/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904834/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904834/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-15","Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the amount of unclaimed entitlement to tax credits in the last financial year.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Sir David Crausby","144188"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904835","Home Office","false","2018-05-21","<p>Individuals in the UK who have indefinite leave to remain or leave as a refugee will not lose their status by leaving and then returning to the UK. They are always required to meet any conditions attached to their status, in line with published guidance: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/browse/visas-immigration" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/browse/visas-immigration</a>.</p><p>When travelling outside the UK, these individuals will need to meet the entry requirements of any country to which they intend to enter.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-05-21T14:26:57.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904835/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904835/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904835/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-15","Immigration: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the rules governing people with (a) indefinite leave to remain and (b) refugee status to (i) leave and then return to Northern Ireland and (ii) to travel to the Republic of Ireland are.","false","Biography information for Conor McGinn","St Helens North","Conor McGinn","144338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904836","Treasury","false","2018-05-23","<p>Government policy on financial education and capability focuses on ensuring that people have the confidence and skills they need to successfully engage with their finances. To this end the Government established the Money Advice Service (MAS), which provides free-to-use financial guidance and coordinates the UK’s Financial Capability Strategy. This is a 10-year strategy which aims to gather evidence and support financial education and capability initiatives that are proven to work.</p><p>Moving forward, the Government has legislated to merge the functions of MAS with those of The Pensions Advisory Service (TPAS) and Pension Wise, to create a Single Financial Guidance Body, which will simplify the existing public financial guidance landscape. The Government’s commitment to improve people’s financial capability and the provision of financial education is reflected in the new body’s strategic function to develop and coordinate a national strategy which will build on and further progress MAS’s work on financial capability.</p><p>It is also particularly important that children and young people receive financial education to help them shape their financial habits later in life. This is why financial literacy was made statutory within the national curriculum in England in 2014, as part of the curriculum for citizenship education for 11-16 year olds.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-05-23T15:39:42.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904836/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904836/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904836/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-15","Financial Services: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans the Government has to improve access to financial education.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Sir David Crausby","144189"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904837","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-05-21","<p>The UK Government recognises the significant contribution that Combat Air makes to UK security, prosperity and international influence and as announced on 22 February 2018 (HCWS479) are developing a Combat Air strategy to address how we will deliver future capability.</p><p>Defence officials are working closely with other Government Departments, international partners, UK industry and academia to inform this work and will publish the initial findings of the strategy this summer.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2018-05-21T15:44:23.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904837/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904837/answer","Hansard Extract 22 February 2018,  HCWS479.docx","Combat Air Strategy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904837/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-05-15","Military Aircraft: Manufacturing Industries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps the Government is taking to ensure that the UK maintains the ability to build combat aircraft and that such capability is not outsourced to foreign powers.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","144223"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904838","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-05-22","<p>We have advised Mr Pickett that we cannot interfere in the Chilean judicial process and have encouraged him to seek the advice of a local lawyer on what other legal recourse may be open to him to re-establish contact with his children.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-05-22T11:42:48.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904838/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904838/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904838/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-15","Chile: Diplomatic Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will make representations to his Chilean counterpart on Martin Pickett, a constituent of the Rt hon Member for Sevenoaks, to help him re-establish contact with his children who are living in Chile.","false","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon","144146"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904839","Department for Education","false","2018-05-21","<p>The information requested is not held centrally.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-05-21T16:21:46.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904839/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904839/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904839/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-15","Children: Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what information his Department holds on the reasons why Morecambe Bay Primary School failed to meet the threshold to retain the support of a social worker team to reduce the number of children on child protection plans to zero.","false","Biography information for David Morris","Morecambe and Lunesdale","David Morris","144280"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904840","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-05-21","<p>The RAF's current manned ISTAR aircraft, while not wholly manufactured in the UK, do include a number of world-leading UK capabilities. Her Majesty's Government is fully supportive of responsible defence exports including ISTAR capabilities more broadly in order to support UK based industry and maintain national capability.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2018-05-21T15:35:48.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904840/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904840/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904840/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-05-15","Military Aircraft: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether the Government has made an assessment of the export potential of operational RAF-manned ISTAR aircraft manufactured in part or entirely in the UK.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","144224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904841","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-05-23","<p>The information requested is not readily available and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>We engage at a personal and individual level with all of our claimants and are committed to tailoring the support that we give, and any conditionality requirements to the specific circumstances of the individuals. Sanctions are only used in a minority of cases and when people fail to meet their conditionality requirements without good reason.</p><p> </p><p>A Decision Maker will take all the claimant’s individual circumstances, including any health conditions or disabilities and any evidence they provide, into account before deciding whether a sanction is warranted.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-05-23T15:20:55.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904841/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904841/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904841/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-15","Social Security Benefits: Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many sanctions have been imposed on (a) jobseekers allowance and (b) universal credit claimants who are experiencing mental health problems in the most recent 12 months for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Sir David Crausby","144190"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904842","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-05-21","<p>The information requested is not readily available and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-05-21T13:50:50.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904842/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904842/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904842/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-15","Universal Credit: Self-employed","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate she has made of the number of self-employed claimants on universal credit full service who have remained self-employed once the Minimum Income Floor is applied at the end of their first 12 months of trading.","false","Biography information for Mike Amesbury","Weaver Vale","Mike Amesbury","144410"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904843","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-22","<p>Defra Group Commercial is in the process of rewriting its Procurement Policy to reflect changes to policy and best practice. The Procurement Policy document will include the use of secondary materials in the purchasing and supply of new products for future procurements. Once completed this document will be accessible on the internet.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-05-22T14:27:46.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904843/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904843/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904843/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-15","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether his Department’s procurement policy takes account of the use of secondary materials in the purchasing of new products; and if he will he make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","144166"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904844","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-23","<p>Defra is the lead department for coordinating the Greening Government Commitments, which set out the actions UK government departments and their agencies will take to reduce their impacts on the environment. Progress towards targets is reported in the Annual Report on the Greening Government Commitments. These commitments include specific requirements for departments to report on how sustainability is embedded in their procurement policies and procedures, including managing sustainability risks within the supply chain.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s 25 Year Environment Plan, published in January 2018, includes a commitment to remove all single use consumer plastics from central government offices. This commitment will be delivered and reported under the sustainable procurement reporting section of the Greening Government Commitments. A number of departments, including Defra, are already taking steps to eliminate single use consumer plastics from their operations. Plastic drinking cups have been removed from Defra offices and replaced by glasses, and plastic coffee cups are soon to be banned from office catering outlets. The department is currently tendering for a new catering contract which will prohibit single use plastics from the summer of 2018.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-05-23T16:24:26.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904844/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904844/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904844/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-15","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to promote sustainable procurement throughout government; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","144167"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904845","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-21","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer given to the hon. Member for Stroud, Dr David Drew, on 16 January 2018, PQ UIN 122061.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-05-21T09:32:51.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904845/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904845/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904845/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-15","Recycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether he plans to review the potential merits of alternatives to weight based recycling targets as part of his Department’s future resources and waste strategy; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","144168"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904846","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-22","<p>We expect the final Circular Economy Package to be adopted on 22 May. The Government has confirmed that the UK will vote in favour of the final package and is currently developing its approach to transposing the package, which we shall set out in the Resources and Waste Strategy later this year.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-05-22T14:08:18.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904846/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904846/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904846/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-15","Waste Management: EU Action","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what his policy is on adopting the future EU circular economy package; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","144169"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904847","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-22","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Government does not comment on Cabinet discussions. The Secretary of State along with several other Cabinet Ministers attended the inaugural meeting of the cross-Government Housing Implementation Taskforce chaired by the Prime Minister.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-05-22T14:25:30.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904847/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904847/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904847/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-15","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether he has discussed with Cabinet colleagues the waste and energy requirements for new housing developments; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","144170"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904848","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-22","<p>I refer the Honourable Member to the answer given to the Honourable Member for Redcar, on 10 May 2018 to PQ UIN 141354.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-05-22T14:30:46.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904848/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904848/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904848/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-15","Animal Welfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions his Department has had with animal welfare organisations since the closure of the consultation on the Draft Animal Welfare Bill.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","144225"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904849","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-05-23","<p>Sport makes a significant economic contribution to the UK. According to my department’s Sport Satellite Account, in 2016 the value of the sports economy was just over £37 billion (gross value added). I look forward to the upcoming 2019 ICC Men’s Cricket World Cup in England and Wales, with games taking place in Nottingham.</p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2018-05-23T12:00:38.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904849/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904849/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904849/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-05-15","Cricket","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate he has made of the gross value added to the (a) UK and (b) East Midlands economy of (i) international and (ii) county-level cricket in the most recent year for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Edward Argar","Charnwood","Edward Argar","144315"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904850","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-05-21","<p>Her Majesty’s Prisons and Probation Service (HMPPS), formerly known as the National Offender Management Service, does not calculate separately the costs of incarcerating perpetrators of acid attacks, knife attacks and violent crimes. The information recorded on the HMPPS central accounting system does not allow the identification of such costs.</p><p> </p><p>An average cost per prisoner, costs per prison place and overall prison unit costs for each private and public sector prison in England and Wales are routinely published by HMPPS. This information is produced on an annual basis and is published after the end of each financial year.</p><p> </p><p>Information on prison expenditure can be accessed in the Prison and Probation Performance Statistics pages for each financial year on the <a href="http://www.gov.uk" target="_blank">www.gov.uk</a> website. Prison unit costs can be found within the Excel document Costs per prison place and cost per prisoner by individual prison establishment in the ‘Cost by Establishment’ tab.</p><p> </p><p>The most recent published figures for financial year 2016-17 can be accessed on the www.gov.uk website from the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistic%20s/prison-performance-statistics-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistic s/prison-performance-statistics-2016-to-2017</a></p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-05-21T16:10:59.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904850/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904850/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904850/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-05-15","Prisoners: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much has been spent on incarcerating the perpetrators of (a) acid attacks, (b) knife attacks and (c) violent crimes; in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","144147"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904851","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-21","<p>The Department does not hold data in relation to the individual costs of these types of treatments.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-05-21T16:02:06.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904851/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904851/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904851/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-15","Crimes of Violence: Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how much his Department has spent on the treatment of (a) acid attack victims, (b) knife attack victims and (c) victims of violent crime in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","144148"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904852","Cabinet Office","false","2018-05-24","<p>During the financial year 2017/18, our records show that there were 12 instances of male staff in my Department taking shared parental leave. The average length of leave taken was 58 working days. This compares to 5 or fewer instances of shared parental leave taken by male staff during 2016/17.</p><p> </p><p>Shared parental leave gives parents a real opportunity to enjoy the early months of childhood. It is a legal right and enables parents to swap some of their maternity or adoption leave and to take the rest more flexibly and as a couple. The Civil Service goes beyond the statutory minimum provision and offers an occupational rate of pay for some of this leave.</p><p> </p><p>The Cabinet Office is committed to being a good modern employer and to offering employees and family friendly employment policies that support business needs. This approach supports employee motivation and work life balance. It also helps retain talented employees.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-05-24T11:15:57.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904852/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904852/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904852/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-05-15","Cabinet Office: Paternity Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many male staff of his Department have taken shared parental leave; and what the average length was of that leave.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","144319"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904853","Treasury","false","2018-05-23","<p>The number of male staff to take shared parental leave in the period April 2017 to March 2018 inclusive was 11 and the average length of time taken was 82 days</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2018-05-23T14:39:40.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904853/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904853/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904853/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-15","Treasury: Paternity Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many male staff of his Department have taken shared parental leave; and what the average length of that leave was.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","144320"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904854","Home Office","false","2018-07-02","<p>Since 5 April 2015, 84 male staff in the Home Office have taken shared parental leave; and the average length of that leave was 13 weeks.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-07-02T13:31:38.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904854/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904854/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904854/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-15","Home Office: Parental Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many male staff of his Department have taken shared parental leave; and what the average length of that leave was.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","144321"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904855","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-05-22","<p>Since the legislation was introduced on 5 April 2015, 29 male UK Based staff members have taken shared parental leave. The average length of leave was 11 weeks.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-05-22T15:38:37.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904855/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904855/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904855/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-15","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Paternity Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many male staff of his Department have taken shared parental leave; and what the average length of that leave was.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","144322"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904856","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-05-22","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union is committed to providing family friendly employment policies to its staff. Shared parental leave provides real flexibility to parents in how they care for their child in their first year. The Civil Service goes beyond the statutory minimum provision and offers an occupational rate of pay for some of this leave.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Fewer than 5 individuals have taken shared parental leave in DExEU the last year and therefore the Department is not in a position to release this information as individuals may be identifiable.</p><p> </p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2018-05-22T10:58:26.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904856/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904856/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904856/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-05-15","Department for Exiting the European Union: Parental Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many male staff of his Department have taken shared parental leave; and what the average length of that leave was.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","144323"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904857","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-05-22","<p>Shared parental leave gives parents a real opportunity to enjoy the early months of childhood. It is a legal right and enables parents to swap some of their maternity or adoption leave and to take the rest more flexibly and as a couple. The Civil Service goes beyond the statutory minimum provision and offers an occupational rate of pay for some of this leave.</p><p> </p><p>The number of male employees in the Ministry of Defence who have taken shared parental leave since its introduction, along with the average length of leave taken, is set out below:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>No. of Male Employees taken shared parental leave from April 2015-2018</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Average length of Leave (calendar days)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Military Personnel</strong></p></td><td><p>379</p></td><td><p>81</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Civilian Personnel</strong></p></td><td><p>76</p></td><td><p>76</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2018-05-22T15:05:18.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904857/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904857/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904857/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-05-15","Ministry of Defence: Paternity Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many male staff of his Department have taken shared parental leave; and what the average length of that leave was.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","144324"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904858","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-05-23","<p>MoJ adopted the cross-government policy on Shared Parental Leave (SPL). This was published prior to the 5<sup>th</sup> April 2015 implementation date to ensure that all employees were aware of the new legislative provision.</p><p> </p><p>The SPL policy is published on the department’s intranet pages and is accessible to all employees. The policy is supported by guidance on the process and includes support tools for employees and managers. The intranet page includes links to the gov.uk SPL calculator and the ACAS website.</p><p> </p><p>The total number of male MoJ staff taking SPL with pay, between 5<sup>th</sup> April 2015 and 31<sup>st</sup> December 2017 is 98, with the average length of SPL with pay, being 110 days.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2018-05-23T11:47:07.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904858/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904858/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904858/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-05-15","Ministry of Justice: Paternity Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many male staff of his Department have taken shared parental leave; and what the average length of that leave was.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","144325"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904859","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-05-23","<p>The Taylor Review: Sustainability of English Churches and Cathedrals, was an independent review that considered how these iconic buildings can become more sustainable and ensure that repair works are undertaken in a timely way. The subsequent pilots are testing, over the next two years, the new model of support proposed by the review.</p><p> </p><p>This involves:</p><p>how effective the roles of a Fabric Support Officer and a Community Support Officer can be in both ensuring regular repairs are undertaken and in opening up wider links between listed places of worship and the wider community;</p><p>the level of need for a 'minor repairs' and a 'major repairs' fund;</p><p>how best practice can be better shared between owners of listed places of worship in ensuring these buildings are properly maintained;</p><p>how the Taylor Review model can be applied across all faiths and denominations</p>","Northampton North","Michael Ellis",,"2018-05-23T11:57:39.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904859/answer","Biography information for Michael Ellis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904859/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904859/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-05-15","Churches: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what new models of financing the repair and maintenance of church buildings are being considered by the Government as part of the pilot scheme under the Taylor Review on the sustainability of English churches and cathedrals.","false","Biography information for Edward Argar","Charnwood","Edward Argar","144316"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904860","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-22","<p>The following table shows the number of male staff in the Department who have taken parental leave and the average length of that leave.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Number of staff</p></td><td><p>17</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Average duration (days)</p></td><td><p>112</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Notes:</p><p> </p><p>1. Period covering 1 April 2015 – 31 May 2018.</p><p>2. Figures include periods of full Occupational, statutory and nil pay Shared Parental Leave.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-05-22T14:17:56.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904860/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904860/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904860/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-15","Department of Health and Social Care: Parental Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many male staff of his Department have taken shared parental leave; and what the average length of that leave was.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","144326"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904861","Home Office","false","2018-05-21","<p>The information requested is not collected centrally. It is a matter for Police and Crime Commissioners and Chief Officers to determine how to use their available resources in line with local priorities.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-05-21T16:53:39.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904861/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904861/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904861/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-15","Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much has been spent by police forces on handling (a) acid attacks, (b) knife attacks and (c) violent crimes in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","144149"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904862","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-05-23","<p>Since the creation of the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy (July 2016), 35 of our male employees have taken Shared Parental Leave.</p><p> </p><p>The average length of Shared Parental Leave taken by those male employees has been 90 days.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2018-05-23T14:12:11.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904862/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904862/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904862/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-05-15","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Paternity Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many male staff of his Department have taken shared parental leave; and what the average length of that leave was.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","144327"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904863","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-05-21","<p>Fourteen male members of staff have taken shared parental leave since the law was introduced in April 2015 at an average length of 108 days, or approximately four months.</p><p>Shared parental leave gives parents a real opportunity to enjoy the early months of childhood. It is a legal right and enables parents to swap some of their maternity or adoption leave and to take the rest more flexibly and as a couple. The Civil Service goes beyond the statutory minimum provision and offers an occupational rate of pay for some of this leave.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2018-05-21T15:32:44.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904863/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904863/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904863/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-05-15","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government: Paternity Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how many male staff of his Department have taken shared parental leave; and what the average length of that leave was.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","144328"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904864","Department for International Trade","false","2018-05-23","<p>The number of male employees in the Department for International Trade (including those working overseas and UK Export Finance) who have taken Shared Parental Leave since the department was created in July 2016 was 4 people. The average length of the leave taken was 82 days.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2018-05-23T16:56:42.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904864/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904864/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904864/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-05-15","Department for International Trade: Paternity Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many male staff of his Department have taken shared parental leave; and what the average length of that leave was.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","144329"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904865","Department for Education","false","2018-05-23","<p>Following the introduction of the Shared Parental Leave regulations, 16 male staff in the department have taken a period of shared parental leave, averaging 3.3 months leave each.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2018-05-23T08:54:31.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904865/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904865/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904865/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-15","Department for Education: Paternity Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many male staff of his Department have taken shared parental leave; and what the average length of that leave was.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","144330"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904866","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-18","<p>In the department since April 2015, 11 male staff have taken shared parental leave and the average length was 61 days.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-05-18T14:10:01.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904866/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904866/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904866/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-15","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Paternity Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many male staff of his Department have taken shared parental leave; and what the average length of that leave was.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","144331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904867","Department for Transport","false","2018-05-23","<p>Since the introduction of the shared parental leave scheme on 5<sup>th</sup> April 2015, the Department (including Central Department and Executive Agencies) have recorded 25 male staff having taken shared parental leave with an average leave length of 89.83 days.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2018-05-23T08:47:30.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904867/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904867/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904867/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-15","Department for Transport: Paternity Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many male staff of his Department have taken shared parental leave; and what the average length of that leave was.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","144332"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904868","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-05-22","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions is committed to supporting parents, particularly parents who juggle work and home responsibilities, and have a range of policies in place to support them. This includes encouraging Shared Parental Leave by providing contractual Shared Parental Pay, which exceeds statutory arrangements and reflects best employment practice.</p><p> </p><p>Since its introduction in April 2015, 78 male employees have taken shared parental leave. The average length of leave recorded on the Department’s HR system is 97 calendar days.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-05-22T14:19:51.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904868/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904868/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904868/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-15","Department for Work and Pensions: Paternity Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many male staff of her Department have taken shared parental leave; and what the average length of that leave was.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","144333"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904869","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-05-21","<p>The information requested is not readily available and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-05-21T10:32:34.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904869/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904869/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904869/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-15","Health and Safety Executive: Income","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much the Health and Safety Executive earned through selling consultancy services in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","144150"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904870","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-05-22","<p>The Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport (DCMS) implemented the Shared Parental Leave Policy in April 2015. Since the policy was introduced, 12 males have taken Shared Parental Leave and the average length of leave was 3.5 months. Uptake of Shared Parental Leave has increased each year since the policy was launched.</p><p> </p><p>Shared Parental Leave can give parents more flexibility in how they share the care of their child in the first year following birth or adoption. Working closely with the Parent's Network, DCMS is actively promoting SPL including having all policy and guidance on the intranet available for all staff to view in order to encourage staff to consider using the flexibility.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-05-22T14:42:14.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904870/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904870/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904870/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-05-15","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Parental Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how many male staff of his Department have taken shared paternal leave; and the average length of that leave was.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","144334"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904871","Department for International Development","false","2018-05-21","<p>DFID cannot provide the requested information for shared paternity leave; however, we can provide the below information for paternity leave and shared parental leave in the last twelve months. DFID cannot disclose the length of each period of leave as individuals may be identified.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Paternity (</strong><strong>Home Civil Servants (HCS) &amp; Staff Appointed in Country (SAIC)):</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Number of Male Staff (HCS &amp; SAIC) *</p></td><td><p>HCS Days Lost</p></td><td><p>SAIC Days Lost</p></td><td><p>Total</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>29</p></td><td><p>279</p></td><td><p>19</p></td><td><p>298</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>* We cannot provide the HCS/SAIC breakdown by count of staff for paternity leave as one of the categories is below six.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Shared Parental Leave (HCS Only): </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Number of Male Staff</p></td><td><p>HCS Total Days Lost</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>14</p></td><td><p>561</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-05-21T16:48:35.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904871/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904871/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904871/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-05-15","Department for International Development: Paternity Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many male staff  in her Department have taken shared paternity leave in the last twelve months; and what the length of each such leave was.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","144335"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904872","Scotland Office","false","2018-05-22","<p>The Scotland Office does not employ staff directly. Staff that join do so on an assignment, loan or secondment from other government bodies, principally the Ministry of Justice and the Scottish Government, who remain the employers. Details of shared parental leave taken by male staff is not held by the Scotland Office; this information is held by the parent employers.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2018-05-22T09:16:30.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904872/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904872/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904872/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2018-05-15","Scotland Office: Paternity Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many male staff of his Department have taken shared parental leave; and what the average length of that leave was.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","144336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904873","Department for Education","false","2018-05-23","<p>Colleges use their funding to provide study programmes that are tailored to students’ needs and include employability, enrichment and pastoral (EEP) activities as well as teaching time for qualifications. EEP hours can include activities such as development of employability skills, careers advice and guidance, and pastoral support such as mental health support.</p><p> </p><p>Colleges have a requirement in their funding agreements to secure access to independent careers guidance for 16 to 19-year olds. The government’s careers strategy expects colleges to use the benchmarks published by the Gatsby Foundation to develop and improve their careers provision. We have published guidance to set out in detail what colleges are expected to do. The department is not prescribing how each college fulfils the requirement. There is a wide range of support available, and drawing on connections with a network of employers should be a central aspect of the college’s overall careers strategy.</p><p> </p><p>We have recently allocated additional funding to support institutions to develop their capacity to establish work placements, as part of the preparation to deliver T levels. This will have a direct impact on employability. A number of sixth form colleges will receive this funding.</p><p> </p><p>We recognise that colleges cannot act alone to support the mental health of their students and the proposals in our green paper, ‘Transforming Mental Health Provision for Children and Young People’ to provide additional support to schools and colleges will be supported by over £300 million in additional funding.</p><p> </p><p>In addition the department is actively considering the efficiency and resilience of the further education sector, and how far existing and forecast funding and regulatory structures meet the costs of delivering world-class provision.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","144192 ; 144193","2018-05-23T08:47:56.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904873/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904873/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904873/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-15","Sixth Form Colleges: Vocational Guidance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent assessment he has made of the adequacy of funding for sixth-form colleges to provide careers advice.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Sir David Crausby","144191"
