"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903944","Scotland Office","false","2018-05-22","<p>As a result of the UK Government’s decisions at the Autumn Budget, the Scottish Government’s budgets will increase by £2 billion, providing it with the opportunity to allocate additional funding to public services and growth in Scotland. This builds on the £350 million increase to the Scottish Government’s budget at Spring Budget 2017. Overall, the Scottish Government’s block grant (before adjustment for tax devolution) will have grown to over £31.1 billion by 2020, a real terms increase over the current Spending Review period.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the Scottish Government has now substantial tax-raising powers to vary the levels of tax and spending in Scotland. Once the Scotland Act 2016 is fully implemented, more than 50% of the Scottish Government’s funding will come from revenues raised in Scotland, making the Scottish Government more accountable to the people it serves.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2018-05-22T09:15:22.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903944/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903944/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903944/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2018-05-14","Public Expenditure: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how much match-funding allocated by the Government the Scottish government has not received as a result of that government not meeting its 5 core economic targets.","false","Biography information for Paul Girvan","South Antrim","Paul Girvan","143853"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903945","Treasury","false","2018-05-17","<p>I can confirm that I have today replied to the letter to the Chancellor from the hon. Member for Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle on the tier 4 CAHMS inpatient unit in Hull.</p><p> </p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2018-05-17T16:53:28.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903945/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903945/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903945/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-14","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he plans to reply to the letter of Wednesday 18 April 2018 from the hon. Member for Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle on the tier 4 CAHMS inpatient unit in Hull.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","143864"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903946","Department for Transport","false","2018-05-22","<p>Government is taking new powers through the Automated and Electric Vehicles Bill to improve the provision of electric vehicle infrastructure. These proposals include powers to regulate technical standards of infrastructure to ensure easy compatibility with vehicles, to ensure availability of data on chargepoint locations and availability, and to require provision at motorway service areas and large fuel retailers.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-05-22T16:00:11.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903946/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903946/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903946/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-14","Electric Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will bring forward legislative proposals to encourage people to transition from conventionally fuelled to electric cars.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","143740"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903947","Department for Transport","false","2018-05-17","<p>The Department does not hold a detailed breakdown of funding for cycling and walking by Parliamentary constituency. However, the tables below provide a guide to the funding allocated to local bodies which may be spent within the Easington constituency.</p><p> </p><p><strong>North East Local Combined Authority</strong></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Funding programme</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£m</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Sustainable Travel Transition Year (2016/17) – <em>Go Smarter</em> project which supported cycling and walking to workplaces, schools and colleges.</p></td><td><p>2.343</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Access Fund – <em>Walk to</em> project which supports walking and cycling to workplaces, schools and colleges (2017-2020)*</p></td><td><p>7.498</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p>9.841</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>*The North East Local Combined Authority is part of a joint bid led by Blackpool Borough Council and ten local bodies.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Durham County Council</strong></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Funding programme</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£m</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Bikeability (national cycling training) (2016/17-2017/18)</p></td><td><p>0.198</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p>0.198</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The North East Local Enterprise Partnership has allocated £10.4m from the Local Growth Fund to cycling and walking projects between 2016/17 and 2020/21. This is based on self-reported data received from the Local Enterprise Partnership.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Further funding may be allocated to projects within the Easington constituency from Highways England designated funds or though the Integrated Transport Block or Highways Maintenance Block allocated to Durham County Council.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-05-17T13:45:32.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903947/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903947/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903947/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-14","Cycling and  Walking: Easington","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 8 May 2018 to Question 140051 on Cycling: Rural Areas, how much of the £1.2 billion of funding available for cycling and walking has been allocated to Easington constituency.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","143741"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903948","Home Office","false","2018-05-21","<p>The information requested is not held in a reportable format and we are unable to give an estimate.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-05-21T16:11:54.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903948/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903948/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903948/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-14","Foreign Nationals: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate he has made of the number of non-EU nationals who are in the UK having entered on a false EU (a) passport or (b) identity document.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","143710"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903949","Department for Transport","false","2018-05-22","<p>The Cycling and Walking Investment Strategy includes a breakdown of the £1.2bn of funding that is available between 2016/17 to 2020/21. Many of the decisions on the allocation of these funds will be made by the relevant local body, in line with the Government’s devolution and localism agenda.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-05-22T15:52:15.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903949/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903949/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903949/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-14","Cycling and  Walking: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 8 May 2018 to Question 140051 on Cycling: Rural Areas, how much of the £1.2 billion of funding available for cycling and walking has been allocated.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","143742"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903951","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-05-17","<p>DWP has various systems to hold information on individual Universal Credit claims, such as claimant details; household composition and any work history.</p><p> </p><p>DWP also collect data about mandatory reconsiderations for Universal Credit, and has partially published this specifically in relation to sanctions in Universal Credit Live Service. This can be accessed at:</p><p><a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/706823/benefit-sanctions-statistics-to-january-2018.pdf" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/706823/benefit-sanctions-statistics-to-january-2018.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>However, to carry out the necessary quality assurance in order to publish information across all decisions subject to a mandatory reconsideration on Universal Credit Live Service and Full Service would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-05-17T16:06:54.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903951/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903951/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903951/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-14","Universal Credit: Easington","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 9 May 2018 to Question 140056 on Universal Credit: Easington, what data his Department collects on individual claims for (a) Universal Credit and (b) Mandatory Reconsiderations.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","143743"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903952","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-05-17","<p>The volume of paper assessment only is outlined in the table below:</p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="5"><p>PIP, ESA &amp; UC Paper Based Assessment April 2013 to March 2018</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April 2013 - March 2014</p></td><td><p>April 2014 - March 2015</p></td><td><p>April 2015 - March 2016</p></td><td><p>April 2016 - March 2017</p></td><td><p>April 2017 - March 2018</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>PIP</p></td><td><p>21,722</p></td><td><p>131,865</p></td><td><p>119,458</p></td><td><p>156,082</p></td><td><p>124,117</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>ESA</p></td><td><p>304,488</p></td><td><p>310,010</p></td><td><p>205,796</p></td><td><p>206,195</p></td><td><p>221,894</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>UC</p></td><td><p>17</p></td><td><p>135</p></td><td><p>503</p></td><td><p>1,743</p></td><td><p>10,222</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The figures show volumes of paper based reports that have been completed by the assessment providers on behalf of DWP without the need for a face to face assessment.</p><p> </p><p>When a Personal Independent Payment award is due for a review a Case Manager can, in some instances, make a decision based on the paper evidence without referring the case to an assessment provider. Volumes in relation to this are not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate costs.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-05-17T14:53:12.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903952/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903952/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903952/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-14","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many claims for (a) personal independence payment, b) employment and support allowance and c) universal credit (limited capability for work related activity element) were determined by paper assessment only in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","143744"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903953","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-17","<p>My Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care has regular discussions with Cabinet colleagues on a range of subjects. The Government has consulted on proposals for the introduction of Medical Examiners and reforms to death certification in England and Wales, and plans to publish its response to the consultation shortly.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-05-17T12:48:03.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903953/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903953/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903953/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-14","Death Certificates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what discussions he has had with the Home Secretary on the timetable for the introduction of the additional qualified informants for Death Certification provided for in the Coroners and Justice Act 2009.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","143745"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903954","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-05-21","<p>The Government is supporting the Parental Bereavement (Leave and Pay) Bill introduced by the hon. Member for Thirsk and Malton. The Bill provides for a new legal minimum period of two weeks’ leave, which will be a day one right, to enable bereaved parents to take time away from work to grieve if that is what they need. The Bill successfully completed its House of Commons stages on 11 May and was introduced to the House of Lords on 14 May.</p><p> </p><p>Parents who lose their child in circumstances such as these would still remain entitled to their full Maternity and Paternity Leave and Pay.</p><p> </p><p>The UK has one of the most generous maternity leave entitlements in the world. We believe it is able to cater for a variety of circumstances, including situations where there are birth complications or post-natal incidents.</p><p> </p><p>Government would expect employers to treat their employees with compassion and flexibility during these difficult times.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-05-21T13:51:09.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903954/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903954/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903954/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-05-14","Bereavement Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if she will make an assessment of the potential merits of bringing forward legislative proposals to establish a statutory period of parental leave for bereaved parents whose children have experienced birth complications or post-natal incidents.","false","Biography information for Paul Girvan","South Antrim","Paul Girvan","143854"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903955","Department for Education","false","2018-05-22","<p>By 2019-20 the government will be investing £1 billion a year to increase our hourly funding rates for the free entitlements and delivery of 30 hours of free childcare. This will take the amount the government spends on early years’ education to around £6 billion by 2019-20 – the highest ever amount. These funding rates are based on our ‘Review of Childcare Costs’, which was described as “thorough and wide ranging” by the National Audit Office. This looked at both the current costs of childcare provision and the implications of future cost pressures facing the sector, including the National Living Wage.</p><p> </p><p>We continue to monitor delivery costs of our early years’ entitlements and have commissioned new research to provide us with robust and detailed cost data from a representative sample of early years providers, which will be published in due course. We continue to monitor local authority funding of providers via the collection of data on their annual planned budget.</p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-05-22T16:14:12.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903955/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903955/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903955/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-14","Pre-school Education: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if his Department will make an assessment of the adequacy of the level of local authority early years funding rates in advance of the start of the next school year.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Sir David Crausby","143666"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903956","Department for Education","false","2018-05-22","<p>We are investing a record amount into the early years sector, spending around £6 billion per year by 2019-20, which includes £1 billion a year to deliver 30 hours of free childcare and increase our hourly funding rates that we introduced in April 2017. The government has also increased Small Business Rate Relief and provided local authorities with funding to support £300 million of discretionary business rates relief. Local authorities are able to use this to support local nurseries.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-05-22T15:20:42.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903956/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903956/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903956/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-14","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether the Government plans to provide business rates relief to childcare providers.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Sir David Crausby","143667"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903957","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-05-22","<p>Many micro businesses do not pay business rates, as they do not occupy rateable property or they benefit from Small Business Rates Relief (SBRR). SBRR was doubled to 100 per cent for businesses with rateable values under £12,000 from April 2017, meaning 600,000 small businesses now pay no business rates. Furthermore, all business, including micro businesses, will benefit from the Government’s decision to bring forward the switch of the annual indexation of business rates from RPI to CPI by two years to April 2018.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak",,"2018-05-22T16:10:00.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903957/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903957/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903957/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-05-14","Small Businesses: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what support his Department provides to micro businesses to manage their business rates.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Sir David Crausby","143668"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903959","Treasury","false","2018-05-21","<p>The Government believes that it is right that a history of paying rent should be recorded and recognised in tenants’ credit scores and in affordability assessments<strong>.</strong></p><p> </p><p>At Autumn Budget 2017, the Government announced the Rent Recognition Challenge, a £2m competition challenging the UK’s world-leading FinTech firms to develop innovative solutions to enable rental tenants to share their rental payment data with lenders and Credit Reference Agencies (CRAs). CRAs maintain a database on consumers’ credit history, and this information is used to help lenders make an assessment of how likely the individual is to repay any credit that is offered.</p><p> </p><p>The 6 successful applicants selected to receive an initial round of grant funding were announced in March.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-05-21T13:32:27.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903959/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903959/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903959/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-14","Rents: Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of establishing a rent recognition database to be regulated by the Financial Conduct Authority.","false","Biography information for Paul Girvan","South Antrim","Paul Girvan","143855"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903960","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-05-22","<p>Help to Buy Equity Loan has helped almost 159,000 households buy a new-build home since spring 2013, with 81 per cent of sales being to first-time buyers. This scheme is for new build homes and is not available for houseboats. There are no plans to extend the scheme to such dwellings.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-05-22T12:59:44.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903960/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903960/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903960/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-05-14","Help to Buy Scheme: Houseboats","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of extending the help-to-buy to scheme to people purchasing house boats as their main residence.","false","Biography information for Paul Girvan","South Antrim","Paul Girvan","143856"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903961","Department for Education","false","2018-05-22","<p>My right hon. Friend, the Secretary of State has met with two small business owners in the childcare sector since his appointment on 8 January 2017. My right hon. Friend, the Secretary of State and I have visited a range of childcare providers since our appointments and continue to engage regularly with representatives from the sector.</p><p><strong><br> </strong></p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-05-22T15:15:03.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903961/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903961/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903961/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-14","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many meetings he has had with small business owners in the childcare sector in each of the last two years.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Sir David Crausby","143669"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903962","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-21","<p>The target for accident and emergency (A&amp;E) performance is for 95% of patients to be admitted, transferred or discharged within four hours of arrival at A&amp;E departments. This target applies throughout the year, not just over the winter period. There is no such thing as A&amp;E winter pressure targets.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England publishes monthly performance data against the standard at both national and NHS trust level for trusts within England. This data is available via the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/ae-waiting-times-and-activity/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/ae-waiting-times-and-activity/</a></p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-05-21T14:23:05.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903962/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903962/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903962/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-14","NHS Trusts: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, which NHS Trusts met their A&E winter pressure targets over the last winter period.","false","Biography information for Paul Girvan","South Antrim","Paul Girvan","143857"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903963","Home Office","false","2018-05-16","<p>Border Force Central Region Canine Detection units in conjunction with Heathrow’s unit regularly deploy to both postal depots at Heathrow Worldwide Distribution Centre and Coventry. The dogs deployed are trained on Drugs, Cash, Tobacco and Firearms</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-05-16T16:07:23.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903963/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903963/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903963/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-14","Drugs: Postal Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if he will made an assessment of the potential merits of deploying canine detection units at Post Office depots to detect the shipment of drugs from online vendors.","false","Biography information for Paul Girvan","South Antrim","Paul Girvan","143858"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903965","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-05-22","<p>​The economic case for the High Speed Rail Link is clear. However, we believe it is important that the final arrangements for a joint border checkpoint on the territory of the Special Administrative Region are consistent with the principles of 'One Country, Two Systems' and with Hong Kong's Basic Law. We will continue to monitor developments closely and to discuss arrangements for consular assistance at the high speed rail terminal with the Hong Kong authorities as the legislative process progresses.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-05-22T13:26:33.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903965/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903965/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903965/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-14","Hong Kong: Railways","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the effect of the proposed  Guangzhou-Shenzhen-Hong Kong Express Rail Link Bill on (a) British citizens residing in Hong Kong, (b) Hong Kong civil society and (c) the principle of one country two systems.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","143649"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903966","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-05-17","<p>Established practice is that the Northern Ireland Office is officially informed about Irish Government visits to Northern Ireland by the Irish Side of the British Irish Intergovernmental Secretariat. With regard to visits to the rest of the UK, the practice is for the Irish Government to arrange routine visits through the Irish Embassy in London, with the FCO providing support for State and Guest of Government visits.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2018-05-17T15:00:46.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903966/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903966/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903966/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-05-14","Official Visits: Republic of Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, if she will publish the guidance on protocol for members of the Irish Government visiting in an official capacity (a) Northern Ireland and (b) other parts of the UK .","false","Biography information for Paul Girvan","South Antrim","Paul Girvan","143859"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903967","Department for Education","false","2018-05-18","<p>As indicated in my answer to question 136295, the current children’s centre statutory guidance says that local councils should update their children’s centre data on a regular basis to reflect any changes to provision. We believe that this is fit for purpose and do not believe it is necessary to place an explicit requirement on local authorities to report children’s centre closures in ‘real time’.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-05-18T13:56:47.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903967/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903967/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903967/answer","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903967/answer/previousversion/58803","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","60","Education","Education","2018-05-14","Children's Centres: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 23 April 2018 to Question 136295 on Children’s Centres: Closures, what assessment has been made of the potential merits of requiring local authorities to report children’s centre closures in real time.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","143822"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903968","Home Office","false","2018-05-16","<p>Section 40 of the British Nationality Act 1981 allows for the deprivation of citizenship where it is conducive to the public good. This includes instances where the individual has conducted themselves in a manner that is seriously prejudicial to the vital interests of the UK; for example, being convicted of serious criminality.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-05-16T16:02:56.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903968/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903968/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903968/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-14","British Nationality: Disqualification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of removing British citizenship from people convicted of serious crimes who obtained British citizenship as a second nationality.","false","Biography information for Paul Girvan","South Antrim","Paul Girvan","143860"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903969","Treasury","false","2018-05-22","<p>The government is determined that everyone who is entitled to the National Minimum and Living Wage (NMW) receives it. Anyone who feels they have been underpaid NMW should contact the Acas helpline on 0300 123 1100 or use the online pay and work rights complaints form on <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/pay-and-work-rights-complaints" target="_blank">gov.uk</a>. HMRC review all complaints that are referred to them.</p><p> </p><p>In 2017/18 HMRC identified over £15.6 million arrears for over 200,000 workers. This included around £5.9 million self-correction arrears affecting around than 72,000 workers.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC always takes action to ensure workers receive what they are entitled to, and has robust assurance processes in place to make sure that all employers fully repay their workers. If HMRC believes that the employer has not self-corrected completely, or becomes aware of another NMW risk, the employer will be investigated again</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-05-22T07:45:05.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903969/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903969/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903969/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-14","Minimum Wage: Arrears","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the HM Revenue and Customs press release of 9 May 2018, 200,000 receive back pay as HMRC enforces National Minimum Wage, how much of the £15.6 million of minimum wage arrears identified in 2017-18 was identified through self-correction by employers; and how many of those 200,000 people those arrears self-corrected by employers relate to.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","143732"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903970","Department for Education","false","2018-05-22","<p>The information on the number of children in families who have no recourse to public funds is not held centrally.</p><p>Free school meals are available to disadvantaged families in receipt of certain qualifying benefits, including children of immigrants and refugees who are receiving support under Part VI of the Immigration &amp; Asylum Act 1999.</p><p>Decisions as to whether immigrants or refugees have recourse to public funds and/or receive support under Part VI of the Immigration &amp; Asylum Act 1999 are made by the Home Office. The Home Office is able to exercise discretion to grant recourse to public funds where the family would otherwise be destitute. Where this entitles the family to receive certain benefits they may also be able to claim free school meals.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-05-22T16:15:20.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903970/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903970/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903970/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-14","Free School Meals: Immigrants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what information his Department holds on the number of children in families with the legal right to remain in the UK with an attached no recourse to public funds condition on their leave to remain who are unable to access free school meals; and what plans the Government has to review the policy and practice in those circumstances.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","143733"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903971","Department for Education","true","2018-05-22","<p>There are currently 393 free schools open. Since 2010, eight free schools have closed. and one closure is planned for summer 2018. The primary objective of the department when making a decision to close a school is to ensure the best possible educational outcomes for pupils and to secure value for money for the taxpayer.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Academic year</p></td><td><p>Free school closures</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>Discovery New School</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>The Durham Free School, Dawes Lane Academy, Stockport Technical School</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>St Michael’s Secondary School</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>Bolton Wanderers Free School, Collective Spirit Free School</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><ins class="ministerial">Southwark Free School</ins></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><del class="ministerial">2017/18</del></p></td><td><p><del class="ministerial">Southwark Free School</del></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>8</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-05-22T16:02:35.693Z","2018-06-15T08:12:03.543Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903971/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903971/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903971/answer","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903971/answer/previousversion/59530","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","60","Education","Education","2018-05-14","Free Schools: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many free schools have closed in each year for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Sir David Crausby","143670"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903972","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-05-22","<p>On 6 April 2018 regulations made under the Housing and Planning Act 2016 came into force, introducing banning orders for landlords who have committed serious offences or who are prolific offenders.</p><p>Local authorities can now apply to the First Tier Tribunal for a banning order against a landlord who has committed a specified banning order offence. Banning order offences include serious criminal offences and housing offences under the Housing Act 2004. If the Tribunal decides to issue an order, it will determine the length of the banning order which must be for a minimum period of 12 months with no upper limit.</p><p>We have published guidance to assist local housing authorities to understand and use their new powers.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2018-05-22T13:04:13.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903972/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903972/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903972/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-05-14","Landlords: Convictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, if he will bring forward legislative proposals to ban landlords with convictions for serious offences from renting out their property.","false","Biography information for Paul Girvan","South Antrim","Paul Girvan","143861"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903974","Department for Education","false","2018-05-22","<p>All children, no matter where they live, should have access to the same high quality care and support to meet their needs. This includes stronger initial training and clarity about the knowledge and skills social workers need in their jobs, and creating an environment where innovation can flourish and frontline practice is driven by evidence. The government continues to implement its reform programme as set out in Putting Children First (2016). We are also taking decisive action to improve services in inadequate local authorities through our interventions programme and by implementing a new improvement strategy for local authorities at risk of failing.</p><p> </p><p>The government recently launched a review into the outcomes of children in need, publishing extensive data on the educational outcomes of this cohort and launching a call for evidence. The review’s work continues, and we are engaging with professionals and organisations who support children in need and with 3 What Works Centres - the Education Endowment Foundation, Early Intervention Foundation, and the What Works Centre for Children’s Social Care - to build our national evidence base on how best to improve these outcomes.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","143760","2018-05-22T15:44:24.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903974/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903974/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903974/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-14","Children: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps he is taking to improve the support provided to children in need.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","143759"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903975","Department for Education","false","2018-05-22","<p>All children, no matter where they live, should have access to the same high quality care and support to meet their needs. This includes stronger initial training and clarity about the knowledge and skills social workers need in their jobs, and creating an environment where innovation can flourish and frontline practice is driven by evidence. The government continues to implement its reform programme as set out in Putting Children First (2016). We are also taking decisive action to improve services in inadequate local authorities through our interventions programme and by implementing a new improvement strategy for local authorities at risk of failing.</p><p> </p><p>The government recently launched a review into the outcomes of children in need, publishing extensive data on the educational outcomes of this cohort and launching a call for evidence. The review’s work continues, and we are engaging with professionals and organisations who support children in need and with 3 What Works Centres - the Education Endowment Foundation, Early Intervention Foundation, and the What Works Centre for Children’s Social Care - to build our national evidence base on how best to improve these outcomes.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","143759","2018-05-22T15:44:24.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903975/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903975/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903975/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-14","Children: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps he is taking to improve the outcomes of children in need.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","143760"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903976","Department for Education","false","2018-05-22","<p>The government is committed to preparing vulnerable children for adult life and recognises the challenges and importance of transition. The statutory guidance, Working Together to Safeguard Children, makes it clear that when children on child protection plans reach the age of eighteen, local authorities should consider whether support services are still required. For children leaving care, the offer of support from local authorities now extends to twenty-five.</p><p>We are already delivering a major programme of reform, as set out in Putting Children First (2016). We are working to improve the quality of the workforce, develop and spread innovative practice, and improve the quality of local authority children’s services. We are also using the Department for Education’s Social Care Innovation Programme to trial programmes to improve the quality of support for adolescents.</p><p>On 16 March the government launched a review into the outcomes of children in need and opened a call for evidence. We will consider the full range of views we receive in response to the call for evidence, including any around transition support and the way this is planned by local authorities.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","144402 ; 144977","2018-05-22T16:56:02.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903976/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903976/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903976/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-14","Children: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether his Department has made an assessment of the potential merits of introducing transition support for children in need.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","143761"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903977","Department for Education","false","2018-05-22","<p>The Government wants as many pupils as possible to benefit from the life-changing activities offered by becoming a Cadet. The Cadet Expansion Programme was launched in June 2012 with the aim to deliver 100 new Combined Cadet Force units in state-funded schools by September 2015. This initial target was delivered six months early, in March 2015. The Government has committed to extend the number of cadet units in UK schools to 500 by March 2020 and the Department is on track to meet this target, with 453 school cadet units established so far.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-05-22T15:36:40.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903977/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903977/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903977/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-14","Combined Cadet Force","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps he is taking to encourage the establishment of Combined Cadet Force units in state schools; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Leo Docherty","Aldershot","Leo Docherty","143824"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903979","Home Office","false","2018-07-02","<p>We are absolutely committed to tackling county lines. The action we are taking is set out in the Serious Violence Strategy published on 9 April. <br>We are delivering a cross-Government and agency programme of work to tackle county lines through the County Lines Action Plan (which is published as an Annex to the Serious Violence Strategy). Last December we introduced the Drug Dealing Telecommunications Restriction Orders to enable police to shut down phone lines used to facilitate drug deals, and we have announced funding of £3.6million to establish a new National County Lines Co-Ordination Centre. Raising awareness of county lines and the appropriate safeguarding response is also very important. In July last year we published guidance on county lines for frontline practitioners to help them identify and respond to county lines exploitation and we are currently delivering a nationwide awareness-raising communications campaign.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-07-02T13:34:28.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903979/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903979/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903979/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-14","Drugs: Organised Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what progress is being made in tackling county lines criminal activity; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Leo Docherty","Aldershot","Leo Docherty","143825"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903980","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-21","<p>The Joint Committee on Vaccination and Immunisation (JCVI) code of practice states that the agenda for a JCVI meeting is published about one week before the meeting. The next meeting will be held on 6 June 2018.</p><p> </p><p>The JCVI code of practice is available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/groups/joint-committee-on-vaccination-and-immunisation" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/groups/joint-committee-on-vaccination-and-immunisation</a></p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-05-21T14:20:21.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903980/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903980/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903980/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-14","Joint Committee On Vaccination and Immunisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what time timetable for the agenda of the next meeting of the Joint Committee on Vaccination and Immunisation to be published is.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","143696"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903981","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-05-22","<p>There is no reliable data as the Government of Sudan does not release information on its Defence expenditure. In 2009, the World Bank estimated that more than 60 percent of Sudan's national budget was spent on Security and Defence. In the absence of reliable information from the Government of Sudan, our assumption is that such spending constitutes between 60 and 70 percent of Sudan's national budget.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","143644","2018-05-22T14:17:25.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903981/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903981/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903981/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-14","Sudan: Armed Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to the Sudan economic factsheet published by his Department on 26 April 2018, what proportion of the budget of the Government of Sudan has been allocated to the military in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","143643"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903982","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-05-22","<p>There is no reliable data as the Government of Sudan does not release information on its Defence expenditure. In 2009, the World Bank estimated that more than 60 percent of Sudan's national budget was spent on Security and Defence. In the absence of reliable information from the Government of Sudan, our assumption is that such spending constitutes between 60 and 70 percent of Sudan's national budget.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","143643","2018-05-22T14:17:25.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903982/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903982/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903982/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-14","Sudan: Armed Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to the Sudan economic factsheet published by his Department on 26 April 2018, what estimate he has made of the level of military spending in Sudan.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","143644"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903983","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-05-22","<p>​The UK Ambassador to Sudan most recently raised our concerns about Noura Hussein's case with senior members of the Government of Sudan on 15 May. On the same day, we released a statement alongside other EU Heads of Mission to make clear our firm opposition to the use of the death penalty under any circumstances, and recalling the principle of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights that marriage should be entered into only with the free and full consent of spouses. We will continue to raise the case at a high level with the Government of Sudan.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-05-22T14:19:51.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903983/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903983/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903983/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-14","Noura Hussein ","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether his Department has made representations to Sudanese Government on the death sentence of Noura Hussein.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","143645"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903985","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-05-22","<p>The reports emerged after the UK-Sudan Strategic Dialogue. We raised our concerns with the Government of Sudan on 9 May. We reiterated the UK's and the international community's expectation that unilateral cessations of hostilities must be observed by both sides. While presenting his credentials to the President of Sudan on 14 May, our Ambassador took the opportunity to repeat the importance of observing the unilateral ceasefire. The UK Defence Attaché raised the issue with the Sudanese Armed Forces on the same date.</p><p>A communique from the Fifth Round is available on the British Government's website.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-05-22T14:21:54.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903985/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903985/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903985/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-14","Sudan: Peace Negotiations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether the Government raised during the latest round of the UK-Sudan Strategic Dialogue in Khartoum the attack of 22 April 2018 made by the Government of Sudan in the Jebel Marra region in Darfur.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","143646"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903986","Home Office","false","2018-05-16","<p>EU citizens with indefinite leave to remain (ILR) in the UK will not need to apply for UK settled status once the UK has left the European Union (EU). Their incumbent rights and privileges will not be affected by the UK’s withdrawal from the EU.</p><p>However, where such individuals are also covered by the Withdrawal Agreement, they might find it useful to apply to the EU Exit Settlement Scheme to obtain updated documentation which they can use to demonstrate their rights. There will be no application fee for settled status where an applicant has documentary evidence that they have valid indefinite leave to remain.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-05-16T16:05:15.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903986/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903986/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903986/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-14","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether it is her policy that EU citizens who have indefinite leave to remain will have to apply for settled status.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","143621"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903987","Department for Transport","false","2018-05-22","<p>The Department for Transport does not keep information on the details of number of ‘station skipping’ incidents on the Southern network.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-05-22T16:08:16.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903987/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903987/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903987/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-14","Railways: Plumpton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the number of trains that were supposed to stop at Plumpton but did not do so between 1 January and May 1 2018.","false","Biography information for Maria Caulfield","Lewes","Maria Caulfield","143806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903988","Home Office","false","2018-05-17","<p>Information provided as part of the Call for Evidence will only be used to inform the design options and scope of the compensation scheme. It will not be used for the purposes of immigration enforcement or affect individual’s access to welfare benefits.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-05-17T16:28:25.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903988/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903988/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903988/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-14","Immigration: Windrush Generation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Written Statement of 10 May 2018, HCWS674 on Immigration, if he will make is his policy that information in response to the call for evidence to inform design of the compensation scheme will not (a) be used for the purposes of immigration enforcement and (b) affect access to welfare benefits.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","143734"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903989","Home Office","false","2018-05-17","<p>Our first priority in negotiations was to reach a deal on citizens’ rights, which we did in December. This gives certainty to those EU citizens living in the UK, and UK nationals living in the EU, that they can continue living their lives broadly as now.</p><p>We are considering a range of options for the future immigration system and will set out initial plans later this year.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-05-17T12:03:34.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903989/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903989/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903989/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-14","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if his Department will publish an immigration white paper before the Migration Advisory Committee's final report on the effect on the UK labour market of the UK’s exit from the European Union is published.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","143763"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903990","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-05-22","<p>The Department already publishes this data on the Nomis website and it can be accessed on the Jobseeker’s Allowance age and duration page at: <a href="http://www.nomisweb.co.uk/query/construct/summary.asp?mode=construct&amp;version=0&amp;dataset=4" target="_blank">www.nomisweb.co.uk/query/construct/summary.asp?mode=construct&amp;version=0&amp;dataset=4</a></p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-05-22T13:53:32.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903990/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903990/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903990/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-14","Jobseeker's Allowance: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people aged between 16 and 24 in Wales have been in receipt of Job Seeker’s Allowance in each of the last five years; and if she will provide that same data by region.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","143812"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903991","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-22","<p>There are 13 private sector prisons in England and one in Wales.</p><p> </p><p>Complaints about healthcare in all prisons, including private sector prisons, should first be made to the healthcare provider.</p><p> </p><p>In England if a prisoner is not satisfied with the response, complaints can be made to the commissioner of healthcare services through the NHS Complaints Procedure. If a prisoner is still not satisfied they may escalate their complaint to the Parliamentary and Health Services Ombudsman.</p><p> </p><p>At HMP Parc in Wales, the process is firstly to approach the provider, and if the prisoner is not satisfied with the response, to contact the prison’s Director of Strategic Support who will commission Betsi Cadwaladr University Health Board to undertake an independent review of the case.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-05-22T10:45:05.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903991/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903991/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903991/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-14","Prisons: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, by what methods a prisoner who is either serving a sentence or on remand in a private sector jail in (a) England and (b) Wales can complain about their health treatment.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","143813"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903992","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-05-22","<p>As of 31 March 2017, the prison population was 83,263. In 2015 the Ministry of Justice made changes so every prisoner coming into custody in England and Wales is asked if they have served in the Armed Forces. Figures on custodial receptions show approximately 3% of offenders who responded to the question were former members of the Armed Forces. Overall numbers have remained consistent over an 18 month period. Full details can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/702302/receptions-2017-q4.ods" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/702302/receptions-2017-q4.ods</a> (table 2.7).</p><p> </p><p>A snapshot of service history following a data matching exercise in 2010 between Ministry of Defence and Ministry of Justice indicated 77% of ex-armed service personnel in prison were ex-Army, 15% were ex-Naval Service, and 8% were ex-RAF. Information on their age when joining the armed services is not recorded and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>We recognise the unique nature of military service. Prisoners who choose to identify as former members of the Armed Forces are given access to specialist support that is available to them via the armed forces and the specialist charities that work in prisons. This includes support for issues such as post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD), that may affect them following their service.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","143815 ; 143816","2018-05-22T10:53:16.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903992/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903992/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/903992/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-05-14","Prisoners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the prison population in England and Wales was for the most recent date for which information is available; and how many of those prisoners were formerly members of the armed forces.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","143814"
