"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904123","Department for International Trade","false","2018-05-22","<p>The Commonwealth is a strong and powerful network of nations. Intra-Commonwealth trade in goods and services is estimated to be $560 billion and projected to reach $700bn by 2020[1] and in 2016, UK-Commonwealth trade stood at £94 billion[2].</p><p> </p><p>Britain is an international leader on development, and the Department for International Trade is working with the Department for International Development to ensure global prosperity is at the heart of our future trade policy. We are committed to ensuring developing countries in the Commonwealth can use trade as an engine of poverty reduction, and trade agreements play an important role in this.</p><p> </p><p>This department continues to work with Commonwealth countries that are part of the EU’s Economic Partnership Agreements (EPAs) or other preferential arrangements to ensure that there is no disruption to our existing trade as we leave the EU. At the Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting we highlighted progress made in the transition of our trading relationships with these partners.</p><p> </p><p>[1] Source: Commonwealth Secretariat Report</p><p>[2] Source: DIT analysis of ONS data</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2018-05-22T13:53:56.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904123/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904123/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904123/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-05-14","Economic Partnership Agreements: Developing Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what discussions he had at the most recent Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting on the effect of Economic Partnership Agreements on developing countries in the Commonwealth.","false","Biography information for Hugh Gaffney","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Hugh Gaffney","143838"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904124","Cabinet Office","false","2018-05-22","<p>I refer the Honourable Member to the 11 May letter that the Prime Minister wrote to the Inquiry Chair, Sir Martin Moore-Bick, confirming her decision to appoint additional panel members <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">gov.uk</a> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/grenfell-tower-inquiry-update" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/grenfell-tower-inquiry-update</a></p><p> </p><p>The Prime Minister will make the appointments in accordance with sections 4,7(1)(b) and 7(2)(b) of the Inquiries Act 2005</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2018-05-22T14:09:08.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904124/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904124/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904124/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-05-14","Grenfell Tower Inquiry: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps his Department plans to take to ensure that appointments to the Grenfell Tower inquiry panel have the confidence of survivors and bereaved families.","false","Biography information for Hugh Gaffney","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Hugh Gaffney","143839"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904125","Treasury","false","2018-05-17","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) is unable to comment on any investigations into individuals or businesses.</p><p> </p><p>However, as part of its remit, HMRC has a multi-faceted role in identifying and tackling money laundering, including supporting the efforts of other agencies, such as the National Crime Agency, in responding to the activities identified in the so-called ‘Laundromat’ exposé.</p><p> </p><p>Under the Money Laundering Regulations 2017, HMRC supervises those Trust or Company Service Providers (including company formation agents) that do not fall under the supervision of the Financial Conduct Authority or legal or accountancy professional bodies.</p><p> </p><p>The action HMRC takes to discharge those supervisory responsibilities and its wider role in tackling financial crime, including support to government initiatives on targeting illicit finances, are described in a recent publication ‘Report on Tackling Financial Crime in the Supervised Sectors 2015-2017’.</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/704163/Report_on_Tackling_Financial_Crime_in_the_supervised_sectors_2015_to_2017.pdf" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/704163/Report_on_Tackling_Financial_Crime_in_the_supervised_sectors_2015_to_2017.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","143869 ; 143870 ; 143871","2018-05-17T15:04:54.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904125/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904125/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/904125/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-14","Money Laundering","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether HMRC has undertaken an investigation into the company agent that formed (a) Augela Systems LLP, (b) 